<dl id="n56140c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56140c">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56140c"> 140(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ (involucrum, spatha, / perianthum, amentus, / gluma, calyptra) <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n56140c"><li>FW 613.17f </li><li><a href="../../flex/tc/lextc.htm#n56140c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/tc/l39tc.htm#n56140c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n56140c">MS BL 47488-95</ms> </li><li>JJA 63:161 <a name="tcd3" href="../../FF/fdra/tda.htm#tcd3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/tc/tcd3.htm#n56140c">Draft: IV&sect;3.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The principal parts of a flower are as follow: a) the Calyx or cup, the outer covering, the sepals, of which there are six kinds: the <mark>involucrum</mark> or involucre, remote from the flower, often of an umbel; the <mark>spatha</mark> or spathe, sheathed, as of a palm; the <mark>perianthum</mark> or perianth, now usually meaning the calyx and corolla combined or indistinguishable; the <mark>amentus</mark> or amentum, a catkin; the <mark>gluma</mark> or glume, a small, dry leaf at the base of a grass spikelet; the <mark>calyptra</mark> or calyptre, cowled, as of a moss; &hellip; <small> Linnaeus, <a name="LINN" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LINN"><cite title="source">Works</cite></a> (ed. unknown) passim</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
